The first batch of prisoners arrived in Ceylon on 9 August 1900 and subsequently others followed until some 5 000 prisoners had landed. Diyatalawa was the main camp. Mt Lavinia was the convalescent camp while dissidents and irreconcilables were housed at Ragama. A camp for prisoners on parole was also opened at Urugasmanhandiya in September 1901. Hambantota was also a parole camp. Camps were established in India at the following places:

- Abottabad
- Ahmednagar
- Bellary
- Bhim Tal
- Dagshai and Solon
- Fort Govindgarh
- Kaity-Nilgiris
- Satara
- Shahjahanpur
- Sialkot
- Trichinopoly
- Umballa
- Upper Topa


An announcement on May 12, 1900, out of Calcutta, stated that Dijitalwa in Ceylon was being prepared for the reception of six thousand Boer prisoners. Reported by the Evening Post, New Zealand, May 14, 1900.

On May 24, 1900, the Bay of Plenty Times, reported that 250 homeless children were sent to Ceylon where they were attending a Dutch school in Kandy.

On July 25, 1900, the Wanganui Herald headlined the following, 2000 Boer prisoners to be sent to Ceylon.This report appeared in the North Otago Times on November 30, 1900, and gives some insight into conditions and attitudes at the prison camp in Ceylon. The 4000 prisoners in the hill country of Ceylon keep their guards very lively by their attempts to escape or break bonds by quarrels among themselves especially between men of different nationalities and by refractory conduct, leading to imprisonment. The most notable attempt to escape was made by a Frenchman and a Spaniard but within twelve hours they were recaptured. One thousand more prisoners are expected, and then the Ceylon contingent of the Boers will be complete.
