According to the New York Times, February 2, 1902, about 5 000 prisoners were in the camp at Diyatalawa which lies 162 miles from the coast and within about six degrees of the equator. Ã�ï¿½Ã¯Â¿Â½Ã�ï¿½Ã�Â¯Ã�ï¿½Ã¯Â¿Â½Ã�ï¿½Ã�Â¿Ã�ï¿½Ã¯Â¿Â½Ã�ï¿½Ã�Â½ The Boer prisoners are housed at the camp in buildings constructed of galvanized iron with board floors. They all appear to have a sufficiency of blankets. The grounds were surrounded by two lines of wire fence about eight feet apart with the space between the two fences filled with loose barbed wire. The food of the prisoners is exactly the same as that furnished to the soldiers who guard them. The Boers, however, are permitted to purchase anything in the shape of food that they may desire. The granting of paroles is very general to the Boer prisoners - especially to the officers, as they had money enough to support themselves outside the inclosure. The prisoners were a well behaved lot of men, except the foreign contingent. With them there was, once or twice, a little trouble, so that a separate camp was established for the foreigners. The majority of the 5 000 prisoners seemed to be well fed, well housed, well clothed, and well treated, and the action of the Government in receiving their officers as equals must be very consoling to their national pride.

On April 19, 1902, the Hawera & Normanby Star gave the figures of Boer prisoners in Ceylon who had voluntarily surrendered - and presumably taken an oath of neutrality - 4 585.

